      "content": "Yes, historians absolutely debate the efficacy and necessity of the nonviolent approach. Some argue that the moral high ground and nonviolent direct action were crucial for garnering national and international support necessary to force federal action. Others contend that the threat of more militant action was an underlying factor that pressured the establishment, or that violence was inevitable given the level of oppression. Ultimately, the combination of both civil disobedience and political pressure was the defining mechanism of the era.",
